00:09:09.540 --> 00:09:12.080
about the Black Arts
Movement, thinking of Morrison

00:09:12.080 --> 00:09:13.390
and her role as an editor.

00:09:13.390 --> 00:09:16.530
And then I'll read a
poem by Henry Dumas.

00:09:16.530 --> 00:09:19.760
And Morrison was very
influential in making sure

00:09:19.760 --> 00:09:24.460
that Henry Dumas's work
reached the world in a way --

00:09:24.460 --> 00:09:28.510
he was killed very young,
murdered by the police,

00:09:28.510 --> 00:09:31.950
and so I'll read a poem of his
and I'll read a poem of mine.

00:09:31.950 --> 00:09:38.410 position:56%
And then I will share a video that I
created as part of the conversation

00:09:38.410 --> 00:09:43.740
of Black Poets Speak Out in terms
of activism, and that poem is by --

00:09:43.740 --> 00:09:49.930
a visual poem that I made about
Amiri Baraka's poem, "Incident."

00:09:49.930 --> 00:09:52.940
But first Morrison.

00:09:52.940 --> 00:09:59.300
In this here place, we flesh;
flesh that weeps, laughs;

00:09:59.300 --> 00:10:05.290
flesh that dances on
bare feet in grass.

00:10:05.290 --> 00:10:07.180
Love it. Love it hard.

00:10:07.180 --> 00:10:11.540
Yonder they do not love your flesh.

00:10:11.540 --> 00:10:12.840
They despise it.

00:10:12.840 --> 00:10:17.910
They don't love your eyes;
they'd just as soon pick 'em out.

00:10:17.910 --> 00:10:21.620
No more do they love
the skin on your back.

00:10:21.620 --> 00:10:23.570
Yonder, they flay it.

00:10:23.570 --> 00:10:30.010
And oh my people, they
do not love your hands.

00:10:30.010 --> 00:10:37.030
Those they only use, tie, bind,
chop off, and leave empty.

00:10:37.030 --> 00:10:39.700
Love your hands!

00:10:39.700 --> 00:10:41.000
Love them.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.030
Raise them up and kiss them.

00:10:43.030 --> 00:10:44.720
Touch others with them.

00:10:44.720 --> 00:10:46.220
Pat them together.

00:10:46.220 --> 00:10:51.150
Stroke them on your face 'cause
they don't love that either.

00:10:51.150 --> 00:10:52.880
You got to love it.

00:10:52.880 --> 00:10:58.090
You! And no, they ain't
in love with your mouth.

00:10:58.090 --> 00:11:03.810
Yonder, out there, they will see
it broken and break it again.

00:11:03.810 --> 00:11:07.550
What you say out of
it, they will not heed.

00:11:07.550 --> 00:11:11.280
What you scream from
it, they do not hear.

00:11:11.280 --> 00:11:16.270
What you put into it to nourish
your body, they will snatch away

00:11:16.270 --> 00:11:19.300
and give you leavin's instead.

00:11:19.300 --> 00:11:21.220
No, they don't love your mouth.

00:11:21.220 --> 00:11:23.310
You got to love it.

00:11:23.310 --> 00:11:25.950
This is flesh I'm talking
about here.

00:11:25.950 --> 00:11:28.100
Flesh that needs to be loved.

00:11:28.100 --> 00:11:33.030
Feet that need to rest and to
dance; backs that need support;

00:11:33.030 --> 00:11:38.760
shoulders that need arms --
strong arms I'm telling you.

00:11:38.760 --> 00:11:45.280
And oh my people out
yonder, hear me,

00:11:45.280 --> 00:11:50.460
they do not love your neck
unnoosed and straight.

00:11:50.460 --> 00:11:56.660 position:56%
So love your neck; put a hand on it,
grace it, stroke it, and hold it up

00:11:56.660 --> 00:12:02.210
and all your inside parts that
they'd just as soon slop for hogs.

00:12:02.210 --> 00:12:03.870
You got to love them.

00:12:03.870 --> 00:12:08.120
The dark, the dark liver --
love it, love it, and the beat

00:12:08.120 --> 00:12:11.580
and beating heart, love that, too.

00:12:11.580 --> 00:12:14.850
More than eyes or feet,
more than lungs that have

00:12:14.850 --> 00:12:20.800
yet to draw free air, more
than your life-holding womb

00:12:20.800 --> 00:12:28.280
and your life-giving private parts,
hear me now, love your heart.

00:12:28.280 --> 00:12:32.590
For this is the prize.

00:12:32.590 --> 00:12:34.890
For Orlando.

00:12:37.850 --> 00:12:42.130
This poem is by Henry Dumas,
"The Coming of Eagles."

00:12:42.130 --> 00:12:44.190
Let us have eagles.

00:12:44.190 --> 00:12:48.530
Let us have eagles among my people.

00:12:48.530 --> 00:12:52.750
The hot wind has melted
ice and the ice has fallen.

00:12:52.750 --> 00:12:57.760
The cold wind has chiseled
mountains and they have fallen.

00:12:57.760 --> 00:13:04.770
The dry wind has gnawed away
stone and stone is sand.

00:13:04.770 --> 00:13:09.830
The cruel winds have cut
feathers, skin, and bones

00:13:09.830 --> 00:13:12.590
and the sparrows have died.

00:13:12.590 --> 00:13:17.140
Let us have new wings
among my people.

00:13:17.140 --> 00:13:20.600
Let us have bones among my people.

00:13:20.600 --> 00:13:24.450 position:56%
Let us have visions among my people.

00:13:24.450 --> 00:13:31.240
Let us ride the wind
into the high country.

00:13:31.240 --> 00:13:34.580
Let us have eagles.

00:13:40.130 --> 00:13:45.490 position:56%
And this is a -- a poem of mine from
a chat book that I had this poem

00:13:45.490 --> 00:13:50.330
and some other poems
included in recently thinking

00:13:50.330 --> 00:13:54.190
about Langston Hughes and kind
of The Negro Speaks of Rivers,

00:13:54.190 --> 00:13:55.510
which I think is interesting to --

00:13:55.510 --> 00:13:58.650
to think about Hughes and
the Harlem Renaissance as --

00:13:58.650 --> 00:14:03.550
as pre-kind of forefathers and
mothers of Black Arts Movement.

00:14:03.550 --> 00:14:06.210
Aubade to Langston.

00:14:06.210 --> 00:14:12.290 position:56%
When the light wakes and finds again
the music of brooms in Mississippi,

00:14:12.290 --> 00:14:18.920
Africa, Mexico; when daylight
pulls our hands from grief,

00:14:18.920 --> 00:14:21.720
and hearts cleaned raw with sawdust

00:14:21.720 --> 00:14:27.840 position:56%
and saltwater flood their dazzling
vessels; when the catfish towards --

00:14:27.840 --> 00:14:33.260
when the catfish in the river raise
their eyelids towards your face;

00:14:33.260 --> 00:14:37.980
when sweetgrass bends in waves
across battlefields where sweat

00:14:37.980 --> 00:14:43.890
and sugar marry; when we hear
our people wearing tongues fine

00:14:43.890 --> 00:14:50.860
with plain greeting, how you doing,
good morning; when I pour coffee

00:14:50.860 --> 00:14:54.780
and remember my mother's
love of buttered grits;

00:14:54.780 --> 00:14:58.370
when the trains far
away in memory begin

00:14:58.370 --> 00:15:04.400
to turn their engines toward a deep
past of knowing; when all I want

00:15:04.400 --> 00:15:10.070
to do is burn my masks;
when I see a woman walking

00:15:10.070 --> 00:15:14.340
down the street holding her
mind like a leather belt;

00:15:14.340 --> 00:15:19.930
when I pluck a blues note for
my lazy shadow and cast its soul

00:15:19.930 --> 00:15:26.860
from my page; when I see God's eyes
looking up at black folks flying

00:15:26.860 --> 00:15:33.310
between moonlight &amp; museum;
when I see a good-looking people

00:15:33.310 --> 00:15:39.630
who are my truest poetry; when I
pick up this pencil like a flute

00:15:39.630 --> 00:15:42.700
and blow myself away from my death,

00:15:42.700 --> 00:15:50.510
I listen to you again beneath the
mercy of a blue morning's grammar.

00:15:50.510 --> 00:15:58.040
[ Applause ]

00:15:58.040 --> 00:16:03.220 position:56%
And then, the last poem of mine that
I'll read is just one part of a --

00:16:03.220 --> 00:16:07.670
a two -- a two-part poem
called, "Elegy," and there's an

00:16:07.670 --> 00:16:13.050
"Anti-Elegy," and I imagine these
two parts of the poem being,

00:16:13.050 --> 00:16:16.050
as a visual artist, a dip
tick, and so there's one panel

00:16:16.050 --> 00:16:19.850
and then there's another panel,
and together, they make a vision.

00:16:19.850 --> 00:16:23.460
And so the part that I'm going to
read from is an ancestral voice

00:16:23.460 --> 00:16:25.380
and so there is an
element, too, of call

00:16:25.380 --> 00:16:28.610
and response which
is the anti-elegy.

00:16:28.610 --> 00:16:32.470
But I'm just going to
read the first part.

00:16:32.470 --> 00:16:38.120
Elegy. I remember the black
boys and their open hands.

00:16:38.120 --> 00:16:41.060
High fives of farewell.

00:16:41.060 --> 00:16:44.290
I remember that the
birches waved, too,

00:16:44.290 --> 00:16:50.530
the white jagged limbs turning
away from incessant wildfires.

00:16:50.530 --> 00:16:54.280
The future wavered,
unlike a question,

00:16:54.280 --> 00:16:56.860
unlike a hand or headstone.

00:16:56.860 --> 00:17:01.390
The future moved and the
fields already knew it.

00:17:01.390 --> 00:17:07.730
I remember the war of the alphabet,
its ears sliced from its face.

00:17:07.730 --> 00:17:11.250 position:56%
I know that language asks for blood.

00:17:11.250 --> 00:17:16.380
The children of kudzu, lilac,
the spit of unknown rivers.

00:17:16.380 --> 00:17:20.200
I remember the jury and
the judge of the people,

00:17:20.200 --> 00:17:25.740
the buckshot that blew the
morning's torso into smoke.

00:17:25.740 --> 00:17:28.980
That last morning, I
begged the grandmothers

00:17:28.980 --> 00:17:32.740
to leave their rage
next to red candles.

00:17:32.740 --> 00:17:35.900
I scattered the stones
the trees bore.

00:17:35.900 --> 00:17:41.880
Great vultures came for my children
and black boys were pouring,

00:17:41.880 --> 00:17:46.330
wanted and unwanted, and
missing, yet from the long mouth

00:17:46.330 --> 00:17:51.150
where their voices were forced
to say they were nothing.

