00:48:50.780 --> 00:48:54.150
And I think it's wonderful that,
you know, we have different ages

00:48:54.150 --> 00:48:56.010
and -- and experiences here.

00:48:56.010 --> 00:49:02.550
As -- as an inspiration and
as an artistic influence,

00:49:02.550 --> 00:49:07.770
what did the Black Arts
Movement mean to you

00:49:07.770 --> 00:49:10.700
and I think we can also think of
the Black Arts Movement as dynamic

00:49:10.700 --> 00:49:14.600
and vibrant and still
living with us here today.

00:49:14.600 --> 00:49:20.440
I know for me, as someone who
was just beginning to think

00:49:20.440 --> 00:49:28.670
about the possibility of being
a writer, it meant to me power

00:49:28.670 --> 00:49:31.580
because the -- the
movement was so connected

00:49:31.580 --> 00:49:36.420
to the Black Power Movement and
the political changes of the time.

00:49:36.420 --> 00:49:44.410
It meant to me audacity, democracy,
that anybody could write a poem,

00:49:44.410 --> 00:49:49.270
anybody could write a powerful
poem, anybody could be a writer.

00:49:49.270 --> 00:49:53.620
And particularly listening to
the poems that we heard, it --

00:49:53.620 --> 00:49:59.340
it meant to me that many of
the most difficult and taboo

00:49:59.340 --> 00:50:02.680
and marginalized emotions that we

00:50:02.680 --> 00:50:05.870
as an oppressed people
could actually be the center

00:50:05.870 --> 00:50:08.980
of our artistic endeavors.

00:50:08.980 --> 00:50:12.900
Eliza, you want to start for us?

00:50:12.900 --> 00:50:14.200
What does it mean, you know,

00:50:14.200 --> 00:50:16.510
that's those are some
things it meant to me, but.

00:50:16.510 --> 00:50:17.810
&gt;&gt; Rachel Eliza Griffiths: Sure.

00:50:17.810 --> 00:50:21.880
In the moment, I'm thinking
of the Black Arts Movement

00:50:21.880 --> 00:50:24.510
in terms of -- of lineage for me.

00:50:24.510 --> 00:50:31.370
As -- as an emerging poet, the
Black Arts Movement for me kind

00:50:31.370 --> 00:50:34.830
of collages a lineage of
justice, a lineage of power --

00:50:34.830 --> 00:50:37.270 position:56%
that word, I think is very resonant.

00:50:37.270 --> 00:50:43.340
But also for me a lineage
of imagination that resisted

00:50:43.340 --> 00:50:48.790
and pushed away from the white
gaze and turned its look inward

00:50:48.790 --> 00:50:53.000
on its own, you know, black and
brown skin, and what was at stake

00:50:53.000 --> 00:50:57.150
for black lives, black history,
black culture, black music,

00:50:57.150 --> 00:51:01.970
black art, all of these
different spaces of embodiment

00:51:01.970 --> 00:51:04.510
and disembodiment within
this country.

00:51:04.510 --> 00:51:09.720
And so, as an emerging poet,
looking, you know, backwards

00:51:09.720 --> 00:51:14.810
and also trying to look ahead about
what will poetry be like for me

00:51:14.810 --> 00:51:18.810
or my identity, my
experience, I feel very grateful

00:51:18.810 --> 00:51:28.780 position:56%
that there was this movement that --

00:51:30.130 --> 00:51:38.240
that really changed the energy
of what had come before it

00:51:38.240 --> 00:51:41.670
in very defiant unapologetic terms.

00:51:41.670 --> 00:51:46.460
And I -- I like the funkiness
of it, I like the texture of it,

00:51:46.460 --> 00:51:50.490
the wildness of it, for
me, especially as --

00:51:50.490 --> 00:51:52.710 position:56%
as a poet who does different genres.

00:51:52.710 --> 00:51:54.410
Like, you can be anything.

00:51:54.410 --> 00:51:58.580
You don't need permission, you
don't need authority, you know,

00:51:58.580 --> 00:52:02.220
open up the door and get
it yourself, you know.

00:52:02.220 --> 00:52:06.480
And -- and for me, those poets are
about getting it for themselves

00:52:06.480 --> 00:52:11.580
and using that oppressive
language in a way that said, no.

00:52:11.580 --> 00:52:18.330
And, you know, thinking of moments
when I have been in a room with --

00:52:18.330 --> 00:52:23.040
with Amiri Baraka or am fortunate
enough to be in the presence

00:52:23.040 --> 00:52:27.480
of Sister Sonya and so many
other poets from that time

00:52:27.480 --> 00:52:31.430 position:56%
and to see them even now, there is a
great feeling of legacy and lineage.

00:52:31.430 --> 00:52:34.320
So I'll -- I'll pause.

00:52:34.320 --> 00:52:36.810
&gt;&gt; Marita Golden: The great
poet, James Brown, said,

00:52:36.810 --> 00:52:39.070
open up the door, I'll
get it myself.

00:52:39.070 --> 00:52:41.120
[ Laughter ]

00:52:41.120 --> 00:52:42.480
&gt;&gt; Rachel Eliza Griffiths:
That's exactly right.

00:52:42.480 --> 00:52:43.780
That's exactly right.

00:52:43.780 --> 00:52:45.080
&gt;&gt; Marita Golden: And, you know,

00:52:45.080 --> 00:52:48.730
it's like Black Lives Matter
could be a poem from that period.

00:52:48.730 --> 00:52:50.030
&gt;&gt; Rachel Eliza Griffiths: Exactly.

00:52:50.030 --> 00:52:51.330
&gt;&gt; Marita Golden: You know.

00:52:51.330 --> 00:52:52.630
It could just be a poem.

00:52:52.630 --> 00:52:53.930
It could be a stanza.

00:52:53.930 --> 00:52:55.230
It could be a title.

00:52:55.230 --> 00:52:57.030
Yeah. So that, you know,

00:52:57.030 --> 00:53:02.610
the movement is still
articulate and inspiring people.

00:53:02.610 --> 00:53:04.360
Tony.

00:53:04.360 --> 00:53:05.950
&gt;&gt; Tony Medina: I see it
in two different ways.

00:53:05.950 --> 00:53:07.940
I see it personally on one hand.

00:53:07.940 --> 00:53:11.420
I also see it in the
more philosophical way.

00:53:11.420 --> 00:53:16.380
The Black Arts Movement to me, it
begins on the continent of Africa,

00:53:16.380 --> 00:53:18.670
you know, as people are
getting abducted and kidnapped

00:53:18.670 --> 00:53:22.630
and being placed, you know, in --

00:53:22.630 --> 00:53:27.760
in chains, on the slave
ships, you know.

00:53:27.760 --> 00:53:31.790
Then it comes onto the land, then
you get Phyllis Wheatley and --

00:53:31.790 --> 00:53:34.450
and Hammond and all these folks.

00:53:34.450 --> 00:53:38.150
Then, of course, you have
that big tremendous flowering

00:53:38.150 --> 00:53:40.620
with the Harlem Renaissance Period

00:53:40.620 --> 00:53:43.030
or the New Negro Movement,
as they call it.

00:53:43.030 --> 00:53:49.160 position:56%
So that's where the grounding starts
to begin, and I don't really see it

00:53:49.160 --> 00:53:53.850
as a movement unto itself,
but a continuum, you know,

00:53:53.850 --> 00:53:55.690
it's like the struggle continues.

00:53:55.690 --> 00:54:00.900
The art is always continuing
and it's always, you know.

00:54:00.900 --> 00:54:02.920
Like I tell my students at Howard,

00:54:02.920 --> 00:54:05.630
if you read -- and
this is just poetry.

00:54:05.630 --> 00:54:08.320
We're not talking about all of the
black arts, because it's bigger

00:54:08.320 --> 00:54:11.630
than just the poetry
and -- and the fiction.

00:54:11.630 --> 00:54:19.450
I tell them, if you read the
whole history of black poetry,

00:54:19.450 --> 00:54:25.240 position:56%
you will get everything you need to
know in terms of history, sociology,

00:54:25.240 --> 00:54:28.420 position:56%
you know, people's way of thinking
and how people respond to the times.

00:54:28.420 --> 00:54:32.250
But personally, to me, it begins

00:54:32.250 --> 00:54:37.030
when I first started
reading, seriously.

00:54:37.030 --> 00:54:39.870
Because I didn't grow up with
books, I grew up in the projects.

00:54:39.870 --> 00:54:43.370
In my household, nobody really
read except for my grandmother

00:54:43.370 --> 00:54:48.150
who read the Bible and some
cheap paperback novels.

00:54:48.150 --> 00:54:52.010
So I didn't have any models
as Lucille Clifton would say.

00:54:52.010 --> 00:54:54.810
There were no models.

00:54:54.810 --> 00:54:56.110
&gt;&gt; Rachel Eliza Griffiths:
I made it up.

00:54:56.110 --> 00:55:00.110
&gt;&gt; Tony Medina: So it wasn't until
I really, you know, the 9th grade,

00:55:00.110 --> 00:55:01.410
I fell in love with literature.

00:55:01.410 --> 00:55:04.860
I started reading, and
then some years after that,

00:55:04.860 --> 00:55:10.360
I remember reading, "A Man Called
James Baldwin from Harlem."

00:55:10.360 --> 00:55:14.080
Reading his essays
taught me how to write.

00:55:14.080 --> 00:55:19.110 position:56%
Literally, I -- I would study his
sentences which lasted a whole page.

00:55:19.110 --> 00:55:20.410
&gt;&gt; Marita Golden: Exactly.

00:55:20.410 --> 00:55:21.810
&gt;&gt; Tony Medina: And that taught
me how to punctuate stuff.

00:55:21.810 --> 00:55:25.590
Not only did it teach me how to
write and how to use punctuation,

00:55:25.590 --> 00:55:28.510
but the things that he
was saying, I said, wow,

00:55:28.510 --> 00:55:30.410
that's how my family lives.

00:55:30.410 --> 00:55:33.250
That's how we -- that's
where -- where I come from.

00:55:33.250 --> 00:55:38.600
So it was reading James Baldwin
and -- I don't know about you guys,

00:55:38.600 --> 00:55:40.650
but I used to be one of these
kids that was, you know,

00:55:40.650 --> 00:55:44.580
every time I got depressed, I
would end up in a bookstore.

00:55:44.580 --> 00:55:47.130
That's why, you know, my --
my crib is like a library.

00:55:47.130 --> 00:55:51.850
So I remember one time going
into this bookstore which was

00:55:51.850 --> 00:55:53.260
on Grand Central Station.

00:55:53.260 --> 00:55:56.690
It was both -- it had an
entranceway inside and outside

00:55:56.690 --> 00:56:00.760
of the train station, on the street
and also in the subway system.

00:56:00.760 --> 00:56:04.490
And so I would go there and I
would just, from A through Z,

00:56:04.490 --> 00:56:07.370
I would browse the poetry section.

00:56:07.370 --> 00:56:14.410
And this one time, I'm browsing,
and there's this book faced out

00:56:14.410 --> 00:56:21.060
and it's Langston Hughes, and he's
at his typewriter looking this way,

00:56:21.060 --> 00:56:25.190
and I was like, whoa, that
looks my uncle such and such.

00:56:25.190 --> 00:56:27.360
[ Laughter ]

00:56:27.360 --> 00:56:32.980
So to see, you know, a brown
face on the cover of a book,

00:56:32.980 --> 00:56:37.410
it reminded of when Amiri was
browsing through the streets

00:56:37.410 --> 00:56:40.000
of the village and he
sees in the bookstore one

00:56:40.000 --> 00:56:43.210
of James Baldwin's books and he
sees Baldwin's face on the cover.

00:56:43.210 --> 00:56:45.950
And, you know, there's a
seismic shift that happens

00:56:45.950 --> 00:56:49.570
in your whole psychology.

00:56:49.570 --> 00:56:51.880 position:56%
So it always begins with those guys.

00:56:51.880 --> 00:56:58.070
And then , I went into the
