it memorized as a child.

01:01:31.510 --> 01:01:35.120
And then -- and then
I went off to college.

01:01:35.120 --> 01:01:40.650
That's where LeRoi
Jones happened to me.

01:01:40.650 --> 01:01:42.090
And he really happened to me.

01:01:42.090 --> 01:01:46.560
It was -- it was like riding a
horse and being struck by lightning

01:01:46.560 --> 01:01:50.230
and falling off the horse because
he was doing something I had never

01:01:50.230 --> 01:01:55.630
imagined a negro poet doing before.

01:01:55.630 --> 01:01:57.330
I was just blown away.

01:01:57.330 --> 01:02:02.920
And then, after that, the Black
Arts Movement gave me other models,

01:02:02.920 --> 01:02:09.370
like Heike [phonetic] and the
last poets and -- and what --

01:02:09.370 --> 01:02:12.360
what they did with poetry,
for me, it was not --

01:02:12.360 --> 01:02:20.280
not so much what they were saying
as it was how they were saying it.

01:02:20.280 --> 01:02:22.890
They were -- they were -- a lot
of those -- especially, Heike,

01:02:22.890 --> 01:02:28.560
I must have heard him three times
during my four undergraduate years.

01:02:28.560 --> 01:02:34.100
And his readings were unlike
anything I had ever heard before.

01:02:34.100 --> 01:02:39.470
They were performative in ways
that I had never heard before.

01:02:39.470 --> 01:02:48.180
So that was a very important
direction to be pushed in.

01:02:48.180 --> 01:02:50.130
I wanted to say one thing.

01:02:50.130 --> 01:02:54.190
My mother was always telling
people that I was a poet

01:02:54.190 --> 01:02:57.060
from the time I was 12 or 13.

01:02:57.060 --> 01:03:01.570
And when I was in high school,
Eugene Redmond was teaching at,

01:03:01.570 --> 01:03:06.510
I think Sacks State University,
and Maya Angelo taught there also,

01:03:06.510 --> 01:03:10.010
and my mother invited
Eugene to the house --

01:03:10.010 --> 01:03:11.310
[ Laughter ]

01:03:11.310 --> 01:03:13.380
so I could meet a black poet.

01:03:13.380 --> 01:03:16.700
You know, I was -- I was
a little kid, really.

01:03:16.700 --> 01:03:18.000
I'm sure he didn't what it was.

01:03:18.000 --> 01:03:23.090
But it was a really indelible
moment to have a poet in the house.

01:03:23.090 --> 01:03:27.370
It was kind of like
being blessed by him.

01:03:27.370 --> 01:03:31.880
And then, the -- the last thing
I would like to say is that,

01:03:31.880 --> 01:03:35.840
when I first started writing
really seriously in my --

01:03:35.840 --> 01:03:41.860
in my mid- and late twenties, I
started really writing seriously

01:03:41.860 --> 01:03:49.950
and for several of those years,
I was living in Minneapolis

01:03:49.950 --> 01:03:53.750
and teaching at St. Olaf College

01:03:53.750 --> 01:03:58.080
which is a Norwegian
Lutheran College.

01:03:58.080 --> 01:04:00.460
And -- but in the twin cities,

01:04:00.460 --> 01:04:04.050
Etheridge Knight somehow
had landed in Minneapolis.

01:04:04.050 --> 01:04:06.430
I've never quite understood why.

01:04:06.430 --> 01:04:12.130
And he and Robert Bly
offered a poetry workshop

01:04:12.130 --> 01:04:16.550
which was called The Free
People's Poetry Workshop.

01:04:16.550 --> 01:04:23.760 position:56%
And I was in this workshop for maybe
two or possibly even three years.

01:04:23.760 --> 01:04:28.220
And we met in people's
homes and then at -- at --

01:04:28.220 --> 01:04:31.050
at an arts center in Minneapolis.

01:04:31.050 --> 01:04:35.220
We met as a workshopping group
and workshopped our poems,

01:04:35.220 --> 01:04:38.380
and Etheridge was a really
great workshop leader.

01:04:38.380 --> 01:04:43.240
He was a very insightful
reader of our poems.

01:04:43.240 --> 01:04:48.400
And then we he thought we had
been workshopping long enough,

01:04:48.400 --> 01:04:52.020
he decided we should
go out of the workshop

01:04:52.020 --> 01:04:54.910
and take our poems to the people.

01:04:54.910 --> 01:04:59.070
And he would say, okay, we --

01:04:59.070 --> 01:05:00.370
we're going to meet

01:05:00.370 --> 01:05:04.940
at the such-and-such hamburger
stand next Wednesday night

01:05:04.940 --> 01:05:07.350
at 7:30, show up there.

01:05:07.350 --> 01:05:10.910
And he -- he had a little PA system
with little speakers like this,

01:05:10.910 --> 01:05:13.670
and a little microphone,
and we would -- he --

01:05:13.670 --> 01:05:15.820
we would go into this
place unannounced.

01:05:15.820 --> 01:05:21.390 position:56%
People were there for dinner eating
hamburgers, and Etheridge would say,

01:05:21.390 --> 01:05:23.510
okay, "Yo, we gonna
read ya some poems."

01:05:23.510 --> 01:05:26.040
[ Laughter ]

01:05:26.040 --> 01:05:31.800
People would put their hamburgers
down and listen to our poems.

01:05:31.800 --> 01:05:34.120
Nobody ever walked out on us.

01:05:34.120 --> 01:05:36.360
It was -- it was an -- it was an --

01:05:36.360 --> 01:05:40.080
this was a period of my life
that was so important to me.

01:05:40.080 --> 01:05:44.260
Baraka said that you know a poem
is good when you can tap a workman

01:05:44.260 --> 01:05:47.580
on the street on the shoulder,
you know, with a, you know,

01:05:47.580 --> 01:05:51.050
some kind of a -- yeah -- tap
him on the shoulder, and say,

01:05:51.050 --> 01:05:52.380 position:56%
would you mind listening to my poem?

01:05:52.380 --> 01:05:55.920
And if he listens to your poem and
then doesn't hit you in the mouth,

01:05:55.920 --> 01:05:57.260
you know it's a good poem.

01:05:57.260 --> 01:05:59.300
[ Laughter ]

01:05:59.300 --> 01:06:03.940
And that's -- that's what that
workshop was for me with Etheridge,

01:06:03.940 --> 01:06:09.290
but it wasn't specifically
a black arts workshop.

01:06:09.290 --> 01:06:11.580
The people, I think -- Etheridge

01:06:11.580 --> 01:06:15.620
and I were probably the only
black people in the workshop.

01:06:15.620 --> 01:06:19.810
But the people who came up --
Mary Karr was in that workshop.

01:06:19.810 --> 01:06:22.120
David Wojahn was in that workshop.

01:06:22.120 --> 01:06:25.370
Etheridge taught us so much.

01:06:25.370 --> 01:06:30.660
He gave us his heart
and -- and he --

01:06:30.660 --> 01:06:33.760
I think he kind of
counts as black arts.

01:06:33.760 --> 01:06:37.320
It kind of came at the
-- at the tail end of it.

01:06:37.320 --> 01:06:43.530
But he initiated all of us into
the sense of what is valuable,

01:06:43.530 --> 01:06:46.450
what are we doing as writers?

01:06:46.450 --> 01:06:48.920
What are we doing as poets?

01:06:48.920 --> 01:06:53.540
And his answer to that would
be that we are freeing people.

01:06:53.540 --> 01:06:56.080
We are setting people free.

01:06:56.080 --> 01:07:00.510
And that I guess is the end of
what I have to say about that.

