01:12:13.920 --> 01:12:19.080
And so, I had the opportunity
to make up the assignment

01:12:19.080 --> 01:12:22.580
and my favorite teacher was
Mr. Del Los Rios [phonetic],

01:12:22.580 --> 01:12:24.370
our English teacher.

01:12:24.370 --> 01:12:26.300
He gave us a list of books.

01:12:26.300 --> 01:12:30.860
On that list was a book whose
title intrigued me and I was like,

01:12:30.860 --> 01:12:34.750
what's an Algernon, "Flowers
for Algernon" by Daniel Keyes.

01:12:34.750 --> 01:12:38.690
That led me into reading
everything on the list of books

01:12:38.690 --> 01:12:41.250
that Mr. Del Los Rios gave me.

01:12:41.250 --> 01:12:43.750
And so my first love,
of course, was fiction.

01:12:43.750 --> 01:12:45.970
Then, I don't know,
three years later,

01:12:45.970 --> 01:12:51.320 position:56%
I just found myself being seized by
the muse of poetry and poems came --

01:12:51.320 --> 01:12:52.840
came out of me so readily.

01:12:52.840 --> 01:12:56.090
And it was like, I would
read my fiction and hate it,

01:12:56.090 --> 01:12:58.130
and I would read my
poetry and like it.

01:12:58.130 --> 01:13:01.260
That led me to read poetry
and fall in love with --

01:13:01.260 --> 01:13:04.040
with poetry on the page and
-- and, you know, Dylan Thomas

01:13:04.040 --> 01:13:06.730
and Hart Crane and Emily
Dickinson, and all these people,

01:13:06.730 --> 01:13:09.950
and then Langston Hughes,
you know, changed the game.

01:13:09.950 --> 01:13:14.080
Also Langston Hughes -- I didn't
grow up with children's books.

01:13:14.080 --> 01:13:19.820
As an adult, I grew to really
love the -- the form of, you know,

01:13:19.820 --> 01:13:21.200
the art and the text
merging together,

01:13:21.200 --> 01:13:24.080
so I started just collecting
children's books

01:13:24.080 --> 01:13:25.700
and reading children's books.

01:13:25.700 --> 01:13:28.450
And that led me to writing
children's books, and of course,

01:13:28.450 --> 01:13:29.750
one of my models was Langston.

01:13:29.750 --> 01:13:32.550 position:56%
I said, you know, I'm sick and tired
of dealing with my own generation.

01:13:32.550 --> 01:13:34.550
I want to talk to younger people.

01:13:34.550 --> 01:13:40.330
So that allowed me to do that
because I saw someone like Langston

01:13:40.330 --> 01:13:45.370
who was able to what he
did for adults politically

01:13:45.370 --> 01:13:48.760
and socially also do
it for young people.

01:13:48.760 --> 01:13:50.240
So that was like my model.

01:13:50.240 --> 01:13:55.650
And since I read so -- so
voraciously in all the genres,

01:13:55.650 --> 01:13:58.120
I just always considered myself
a writer so I should be able

01:13:58.120 --> 01:13:59.960
to try to write in every genre.

01:13:59.960 --> 01:14:07.590
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Nelson: I --
I don't know what to say.

01:14:07.590 --> 01:14:11.670
Genre crossing for me has
been -- as I said, I --

01:14:11.670 --> 01:14:17.990
I have written what I think of
as a slave narrative in verse.

01:14:17.990 --> 01:14:23.020
I've -- what else have I done.

01:14:23.020 --> 01:14:28.180
I -- I -- I've done a
biography in verse of Carver.

01:14:28.180 --> 01:14:34.370
I do a lot of history -- African
American History in poetry

01:14:34.370 --> 01:14:38.750
because it seems -- it
seems to be a way of --

01:14:38.750 --> 01:14:40.820
of reaching people
with little scenes,

01:14:40.820 --> 01:14:44.790
little gems of scenes
from our history.

01:14:44.790 --> 01:14:50.230
And a lot of my poems,
especially the history poems,

01:14:50.230 --> 01:14:53.560
have been published for
young adult audiences that --

01:14:53.560 --> 01:14:55.860
that's a marketing decision.

01:14:55.860 --> 01:15:00.260
But I think it's a good
decision because, as Tony said,

01:15:00.260 --> 01:15:02.220 position:56%
we're reaching a different audience.

01:15:02.220 --> 01:15:05.330
You can write for people who are
your own age, or you can write

01:15:05.330 --> 01:15:06.990
for people who are younger.

01:15:06.990 --> 01:15:09.010
If you write for people
who are younger,

01:15:09.010 --> 01:15:11.570
you're both introducing
them to things

01:15:11.570 --> 01:15:17.350 position:56%
that they might not be introduced to
otherwise, you're preparing them --

01:15:17.350 --> 01:15:21.350
giving them eyes to see
the world more clearly.

01:15:21.350 --> 01:15:29.390 position:56%
And I think you're also pulling them
into poetry, making lovers of poetry

01:15:29.390 --> 01:15:33.950
out of them which I think is
-- is a valuable thing to do.

01:15:33.950 --> 01:15:39.960
And the fact that I do
a lot of research for --

01:15:39.960 --> 01:15:43.840
for my books and encourage
young people

01:15:43.840 --> 01:15:48.430 position:56%
to do their own historical research,
I've been at schools where,

01:15:48.430 --> 01:15:53.670
because they had read my book --
books and the work of Karen Hesse,

01:15:53.670 --> 01:15:58.930
who also writes history
based on research.

01:15:58.930 --> 01:16:01.110
I've seen kids do their
own research.

01:16:01.110 --> 01:16:04.730
I've seen -- I -- I was in
a school once where the --

01:16:04.730 --> 01:16:08.180
it was a middle school and
the children had done research

01:16:08.180 --> 01:16:14.270 position:56%
about where -- which homes in their
community -- this was in New York --

01:16:14.270 --> 01:16:18.770
which homes in their
community had held slaves.

01:16:18.770 --> 01:16:21.800
They had done original research.

01:16:21.800 --> 01:16:26.970
They had discovered
things about their own town

01:16:26.970 --> 01:16:32.000 position:56%
that the local PBS station heard
about it and did a program about it.

01:16:32.000 --> 01:16:36.230
These were middle school children
who had done original research.

01:16:36.230 --> 01:16:40.550
And I think that's a worthwhile
thing to do, to encourage people

01:16:40.550 --> 01:16:43.520
to learn about their own history.

01:16:43.520 --> 01:16:48.620
So I -- I guess that's the
most I have to say about it.

